
[1]anatomy

   ANAT'OMY, n. [Gr. through and to cut.]

   1. The art of dissecting, or artificially separating the different
   parts of an animal body, to discover their situation, structure and
   economy.

   2. The doctrine of the structure of the body, learned by dissection;
   as, a physician understands anatomy.

   3. The act of dividing any thing, corporeal or intellectual, for the
   purpose of examining its parts; as, the anatomy of a plant, or of a
   discourse.

   4. The body stripped of its integuments; a skeleton, or the corporeal
   frame of bones entire, without the skin, flesh and vessels; an improper
   use of the word, and vulgar.

   5. Ironically, a meager person.
